Kill Them Now x3<br />
Vengeance x2<br />
Saruman’s Power x2<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(57)">Worry</a><br />
What Did You Discover<br />
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> ***READ STRATEGY BEFORE REVIEWING***<br />
<br />
When I build decks, I try to achieve some very small goals.  This deck, more than any I have ever created, accomplishes those goals admirably.  It rids burdens, discards conditions, avoids bad skirmishes, wins important skirmishes, manages wounds, protects the ring, and it has a shadow side that achieve the same goals on the opposite side (well, it doesn’t rid the ring-bearer of burdens…that would just be silly).  <br />
<br />
How Does It Work?<br />
<br />
Bid 5.  When (not if) you win the bid, choose to go first.  Start Sam, Merry, and Pippin.  Play your starting fellowship and remove 1 burden.  Exhaust Sam to remove an additional 3.  Exert Pippin and Merry to get Aragorn.  If available, play Gandalf or Treebeard.  Gandalf puts you at 6 companions.  It’s okay.  If your opponent plays Enquea, the only people he can kill are Sam, Pippin, or Merry.  If he does, who cares?  You’ll kill Enquea when you move again.  And if they play a Southron Commander, discard Pippin…you’ll get him back with Gandalf.  Kill off Sam at the first available opportunity.  Now, Enquea isn’t a threat.  Discard excess companions.  Take non-directed wounds on Pippin and Merry then use Warmed Up A Bit to “remove” those wounds.  Use Gandalf and Treebeard to bring the hobbits back to remove more wounds and/or burdens.  Have Wingfoot dole out extra wounds.  Use your various stealth events and pumps wisely.  The shadow is all about attrition.  Between Saruman and Weary, your opponent will be exerting companions left and right.  Then, when you start manipulating their assignments in the late game, companions will fall.<br />
<br />
(Note: Just because you discarded a Hobbit one turn, that doesn’t mean that you have to play him, next turn.  You may find that it will benefit you more to play Birchseed and remove all of Merry’s wounds, than to play Pippin and remove one just because you discarded him last turn.  Pick the combination of companions that serves you best.)<br />
<br />
Why Certain Cards?<br />
<br />
Uruk Plains Runner:  Believe it or not Uruk Plains Runners are the fuel for this deck.  They are cheap powerful minions.  Get them to the fierce skirmish and they’re power 10 and damage +1…all for only 2 twilight.  That’s good economics if you ask me.<br />
Servant of the Eye:  Better than Keeper of Isengard in many ways…and as we all know, Keeper of Isengard was good enough to get banned.  Depending on the number of minions you have available, each of his vitality should create a wound.  Many times, his vitality will create a dead companion.  When you figure that you will see him 3 times per game, that’s 2 or 3 dead companions.  You don’t have to be Will Hunting to do that math.<br />
Saruman’s Power:  Somebody will argue that I should play Saruman’s Power or Weary…not both.  Well, I can’t in good conscience play a deck and not play THE counter for its magic bullet (i.e., Fearing the Worst).  Furthermore, sometimes you must realize that discarding all of your opponent’s conditions is more important than preserving one or two of yours.<br />
What Did You Discover:  It’s a cross between Constantly Threatening and They Are Coming—2 of the best conditions in the game.  I’ll take it…and then overwhelm you when you make that second move.<br />
Worry:  All of my minions are fierce.  Could easily set up the Palantir Chamber beatdown.<br />
Kill Them Now/Vengeance:  You’re going to play Weary on their good characters…and if those companions are strong enough, they’ll assign despite the exertion.  Kill Them Now punishes them and makes the offending companion dead.  Vengeance also works in this manner…but it doesn’t always require Weary.  I play more Kill Them Nows than Vengeances because Vengeance can be (and often is) useless.<br />
Broad Bladed Sword:  Throw it on a Plains Runner and watch Legolas, Aragorn, and Faramir just shrug their shoulders in exasperation.  Then, watch as that Plains Runner comes to a second fight as a Power 12 damage +1 minion.  <br />
<br />
White Mountains:  Exerts opposing fellowships so that they can’t prevent Saruman assignments.  Meanwhile, you have lots of vitality to absorb the exertions.<br />
Deep of Helm:  With 3 Saruman’s, you shouldn’t need to pull him.  So, you can use him here and a cheap Uruk swarm to bring the pain to opposing fellowships.<br />
Palantir Chamber:  An early game Worry can cement the victory with this as your site 9.<br />
<br />
Greyhame:  Plays any CHARACTER from your discard pile.  Not only does that mean that I can discard Son of Denethor fist turn and still have him save my @$$ at site 9, it also means that I can recycle Albert Dreary should my opponent surprise me with late Moria or Isengard conditions (and how often does that happen…oh yeah, never…still, you could).<br />
Birchseed:  He’s powerful and he heals Merry and Pippin.<br />
Lindenroot:  Beats Isengard!  Power 10 Companion!<br />
Son of Denethor:  Discard him early and then bring him back, later.  There’s nothing like having to triple a power 12 (or 17 if you can get Merry out of his skirmish) ring-bearer at site 9.<br />
Wingfoot:  Makes the double-moves easy.<br />
Barliman:  Once you have Treebeard and Gandalf out, you don’t need AWiNL anymore (unless you’re playing Moria or Isengard).  And typically (unless you have Servants in your hand), you should go for Treebeard as opposed to Gandalf first turn.  Then, you draw into Gandalf and that extra copy of AWiNL is a wasted card.  Well, instead of it being a wasted card, make it an additional GST or Servant.<br />
Warmed Up A Bit:  With Treebeard and Greyhame, it’s the only Hobbit Stealth that works over the entire site path!  This card has many different uses.  When used correctly, this can easily equal 2 stealths.  Use Merry to keep Aragorn, Gandalf, or Frodo from being overwhelmed.  Then, in a fierce skirmish, assign Merry and discard him.  Next turn, play him again.<br />
<br />
Why Not Certain Cards?<br />
<br />
Grima:  Yes, he fits the deck!  However, I don’t like him because he’s too low powered.  Besides, seeing Trackers, most players will fear Grima.  And if your opponent gets to the Grima threshold, start lamenting that this is why you play Grima but he’s never around when you need him.  You’ll be surprised how often that bluff causes your opponent to start shifting weapons around.<br />
Uruk Searchers:  Honestly, if you had a Weary on your companion, would you assign him to a Searcher.  I didn’t think so.  So, aside from Saruman, what’s the point.  I’d rather have the strength bonuses in the fierce skirmish.<br />
Site Control:  The strategy takes too much in a deck for too little reward.<br />
<br />
Gandalf’s Staff:  The Wizard’s Staff is a strength pump.  I can’t emphasize how important that is.  It gives you a second Merry.  Otherwise, what are you going to use Gandalf’s vitality for, anyway?<br />
Dauntless Hunter:  Remember Grima!  Yes, you could drop Wingfoot for Legolas, but the entire reason I gave up on Dauntless Hunter in the first place was that I didn’t have enough fighting companions.<br />
Escape:  Definitely a good card.  I would like to add it in.  I made a conscious effort to avoid conditions because of GST.  Although that doesn’t negate the power of cards such as There and Back Again, Cliffs of Emyn Muil, or Escape, it’s the reason that you don’t see them.<br />
Discard Hobbits:  It’s a toss up!  I like the Discard Hobbits in this deck, but I like having Merry’s Power adding ability even better.  The ability to win skirmishes can wreck the best laid plans of any shadow side.<br />
<br />
Well, that’s the deck!  If you have any questions, D-Mail me!  If you have any constructive criticisms, post them in your review.  I’ll respond to reviews as I read them.  Good luck with it.<br />
<br />
Devon “Fangorn Welcomes You…Now Go to the Discard Pile!” Clark </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=28681&PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=28681&PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
